eIUM Release Notes

HPE enhanced Interactive Unified Mediation

Release Notes

eIUM 9.0

Contents

  • Introduction
  • What's New in eIUM 9.0?
  • Enhancements and Defects Fixed in this Release

Introduction

HPE eIUM 9.0 is a new release of the industry leading real-time charging and convergent mediation solution that supports a wide variety of billing and charging services on current and next-generation networks, both in batch processing and in real time. For more information and an overview of eIUM, see the HPE eIUM Overview Guide.

This release includes several important fixes to eIUM, which were introduced into the product since the last release. These fixes repair critical defects and they are essential to the proper operation of eIUM. Fixes to defects that are not urgent or critical are planned for a subsequent release.

This release notes document lists the new features in eIUM 9.0, and it also includes a brief summary of each defect fixed in this patch. The defects are sorted in descending order by patch (most recent first) and by defect ID within each patch. Older defect IDs start with "JAG" while newer IDs start with "QXCR". Some defects have both IDs.

eIUM 9.0 can be installed either standalone, or over the previous version (only upgrading from version 8.3 and 8.3 Feature Pack 1 is supported). For more information on installing or uninstalling eIUM, see the HP eIUM Installation Guide.

Software and hardware requirements
NOTE: A new license key is required for every major and minor release to install and upgrade eIUM. All Feature Pack releases are compatible with major/minor releases and do not require having a new license key.
NOTE: The 8.3 license key framework was refactored versus previous versions of eIUM. A new license key is required to install and run eIUM 9.0.

eIUM is a Java application that can run on multiple platforms. This release supports JDK 8 Update 102 or higher.

As an HPE customer, you can obtain the most current software releases and documentation by contacting your HPE Sales representative or HPE Delivery contact. Or, you can open a support case by e-mail to request assistance: iumsupport@hpe.com. Also see the HPE eIUM Installation Guide and for information on software requirements.

The number of hosts required for an eIUM deployment depends on the number of data sources from which eIUM processes data. The disk space and memory required depend on the number and configuration of eIUM components, the volume of data processed and stored, and whether security is enabled. For specific hardware requirements, see the HPE eIUM Installation Guide, or contact your HPE Sales representative or HPE Delivery contact for up-to-date requirements.

What's new in eIUM eIUM 9.0?

eIUM eIUM 9.0 includes defect fixes as described below and the following new features. For details on all components, see the eIUM Component Reference. Also see the eIUM version 9.0 page under the What's new link in the Component Reference.

Charging Manager/Session Server/Connector Components

  • The new Managed configuration attribute has been added to DynamicEndPointSelector, which when set to false, will avoid registering the numerous TCPEndPoints to the management server.
  • SNME support has been added to JDBCQuery, DynamicJDBCQuery, JDBCSessionStore, and JNDIClientConnector, and its operations, while DistributedCachedQuery has been modified wherever required.
  • The new BERRecordIdentifier component has been added, which can be configured under SimpleProtocol to enable parsing of BER records.
  • LDAPConnector now includes new configurable attributes to support connection handling capabilities, such as: adding connection timeouts for bound- and pre-bound connections; limiting the number of allowed opened connections (total and per client); and, providing a configurable buffer size. As a result, the new MaxConnections, MaxConnectionsPerIP, IdleTimeout, PreBindTimeout, and BufferSize attributes are included.
  • The new CeilometerConnector component allows the eIUM Session Server to collect usage data from an NFV OpenStack system (such as Helion). The integration with the OpenStack Identity service manages security tokens, which are renewed automatically for the CeilometerConnector. The new CeilometerEncapsulator and CeilometerNMESource components reuse the CeilometerConnector and allow collecting telemetry data by the eIUM Collector. Meanwhile, CeilometerRequest specifies a bridge to ResponseHandlers. The data collected can be converted into an NME and processed as any other mediation data. This allows building a metering solution for virtualized networks and solutions, and to calculate how much resources each of the v-applications consumed from NFV, and so on. Integration with Telemetry services is based on Telemetry API v2. For more details about Telemetry API v2, see http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-telemetry-v2.html. The Ceilometer API is already deprecated in OpenStack (see http://docs.openstack.org/developer/ceilometer/webapi/v2.html). It is suggested to use the APIs from Aodh (alarms), Gnocchi (metrics), and/or Panko (events) services. The CeilometerConnector also only supports simple queries. No complex query structures should be expected (see http://docs.openstack.org/developer/ceilometer/webapi/v2.html#simple-query).
  • The new NMELinkConnector allows sending and receiving NMEs to/from remote session servers or collectors. The component can send and receive NMEs from a remote NMELinkConnector configured in an eIUM process (session server process or collector process). NMELinkConnector uses the IPDR/SP protocol to transport NMEs. The NMELinkConnector has both the capabilities, that is, it can send and receive data from another eIUM process, and it can send and receive data either using a request-response model or bulk mode. Several new NMELink components have been added to support NMELink functionality. For more information, see the NMELink category of components.
  • ClientConnector EndPoints now have a throttling feature to limit the sending rate of messages to remote servers. Namely: HTTPEndPoint (HTTPClientConnector), JNDIEndPoint (JNDIClientConnector, JNDILookupConnector), SMTPEndPoint (SMTPClientConnector), TCPEndPoint (TCPConnector), UDPEndPoint (UDPConnector), SCTPEndPoint (SCTPConnector), SMPPClientEndPoint (SMPPClientConnector), SMTPEndPoint (SMTPClientConnector), and SSHEndPoint (SSHClientConnector). JMXEndPoint and SNMPEndPoint do not support this.
  • Kafka integration points in eIUM are now available, to send and receive bulk/single NMEs to and from a Kafka broker. See the new Kafka category of components in the eIUM Component Reference, as well as the eIUM Foundation Guide. The supported Kafka version is 0.10.0.0.
  • The JNDILookupConnector new MatchQuery attribute allows configuring complex LDAP queries. 
  • The new SendSMSOnConnectionOpen configuration attribute in SMPPClientEndPoint has been created to allow connection opening and closing via JMX itself, as well as to control the sending of test SMS to the SMPP server, when a connection is created through the JMX operation.
  • The new DiameterRuleChainAuthorizer component has been added. It authorizes all incoming and outgoing connections by calling a rule chain when a CER or CEA is received.
  • Users can create an eIUM license with the throughput value for the RadiusAdapter. If the throughput is provided in the license, then this limitation will be applied on the RadiusAdapter. Namely: 1) If RadiusAdapter is configured as a server, a throughput license policy will be applied on the number of requests received by the server. If the license limit is reached, in the Operations Console interface, an alarm will be activated. The adapter will still work and will not be stopped; 2) If RadiusAdapter is configured as a client, a throughput license policy will be applied on the number of requests sent by this client. If the license limit is reached, in the Operations Console interface, an alarm will be activated. The adapter will still work and will not be stopped; and 3) If no throughput is mentioned while requesting license, then there will not be any business logic executed to calculate or publish the throughput limit. The same license throughput limitation is also applicable for DiameterAdapter.
  • TimerExecutor supports sequence generators.
  • The new CheckMandatoryAVP configuration attribute has been added in AVPDecoderHolder and StructuredAVPDecoderHolder. If the attribute is set to false, AVPDecoderHolder/StructuredAVPDecoderHolder can skip mandatory AVPs in decoding without generating errors.
  • In JsonResponseGenerator, the VirtualRoot configuration attribute has been made a multi-valued attribute.
  • To force TLSv1.2, the new configuration attribute EnabledProtocols has been added in TCPConnector, TCPEndPoint, HttpEndPoint, SCTPConnector and SCTPEndPoint.
  • DiameterAdapter now allows configuring multiple values of the ServerIP configuration attribute. All values of this attribute are sent in the CER/CEA in Host-IP-Address AVP.
  • DiameterAdapter now correctly understands the Relay Application ID, and performs Application ID negotiation according to RFC6733.
  • To support SOAP with attachments, SoapHttpRequest has been enhanced with two new configuration sub-nodes: ContentProvider and ContentConsumer. The earlier MTOM support (EnableMTOMEncoding) has been moved to the ContentProvider sub-node as AttachmentEncoding, which will now support both MTOM and SOAP with Attachments based on configuration.
  • ESMEConnector can now split a message and send it as multiple messages. To support this functionality, new attributes have been added to several different components. The two new LongSMSSplitMode and LongSMSSplitSize configuration attributes have been added to SubmitSmEncoder. Moreover, the two new AggregateSplitSMS and SplitSMSCacheTimeout configuration attributes have been added to SMSCConnector. The two new AggregateSplitSMS and SplitSMSCacheTimeout configuration attributes have been added to ESMEConnection, to turn on aggregation of segmented deliver_sm messages. Lastly, the three new configuration attributes UDHMsgRefAttribute, UDHTotalSegmentsAttribute, and UDHSeqNumAttribute have been added to SubmitSmDecoder and DeliverSmDecoder.
  • SMTPClientConnector now supports file, binary, text and composite attachments. It also now supports specifying an explicit date for the Date header field of an e-mail. SMTPClientConnector also now supports sending of emails over SSL. See the EnableSSL attribute of the SMTPEndPoint component for more information.
  • To support configuring port numbers that can be used for outgoing connections in SCTPMessageTransport and DiameterSCTPTransport, the new OutgoingPort configuration attribute has been added to these components. OutgoingPort allows configuration of one port, or a port range for outgoing connections.
  • The new SMPPClientConnector supports sending of SMS messages over SMPP.
  • SSHEndPoint now supports automatic removal of idle connections from its pool via the new MaxConnectionIdleTime attribute.
  • The new Router configuration attribute has been added in DiameterClientRule. The attribute specifies the name of the DiameterAdapter Router sub-component, which identifies the destination of an outgoing request.
  • SubmitSmEncoder has been enhanced to send the ListAttribute with only one item as a normal message. It has also been enhanced to support ListAttributes as a ShortMessageAttribute. The component will now send each item of the ListAttribute as a segmented SMS. The OPTIONAL_PARAMETERS mode has also been changed to always append the more_messages_to_send optional parameter. The new MaxNumSegments configuration attribute in SubmitSmEncoder has also been added to check the number of segments the message is being split into.
  • The new DiameterSRVResolver component has been added, which resolves Diameter Node names querying DNS SRV records.
  • To support configuring connectors and connection MBean class names, the new StatisticsClass configuration attribute has been added for connectors that use extended statistics. The connector's MBean class name is equal to the value of this attribute. The connection MBean class name is the same value appended by "Connection".
  • NMECacheSessionStore has been enhanced to support VoltDB with partitioned data using the new PartitionAttribute configuration attribute, which should specify the NME attribute with an articular partition value when the store is accessed by the following session rules: CreateSessionRule, LookupSessionRule, UpdateSessionRule and DeleteSessionRule.
  • For the SNMPAgent component, it is now possible to configure the community string for sending SNMP traps.
  • Enhancements implemented in the NME RPC client adapter are the following: (1) End point configuration is removed. For each send operation, the router will resolve all the possible destinations for the current request; (2) Message type will not be coupled with end points; and (3) There is no primary-secondary dedicated end points, as the end point is not configured under the adapter. End points will be provided by the router to the adapter (based on the list of destinations returned from the router). The adapter will decide the priority of destination.
  • The following new configurable Diameter statistics components have been added: ProtocolErrorResponsesSentStats, ProtocolErrorResponsesReceivedStats, DiameterBusyResponsesSentStats, NumLostResponsesStats, NumUnexpectedResponsesStats, and TotalReconnectionAttemptsStats. These components calculate the following statistics, which have been removed from DiameterAdapter itself: ProtocolErrorResponsesSent, ProtocolErrorResponsesReceived, DiameterBusyResponsesSent, NumLostResponses, NumUnexpectedResponses, and TotalReconnectionAttempts. DiameterAdapter alarms and thresholds have also been removed. The new CompositeStatistics statistics component has also been added, which allows configuring other statistics components as its sub-nodes.
  • The following generic statistics components have been added:
    • BasicClientStats with statistics: TotalRequestsSent - Number of sent requests.
    • TotalResponsesReceived - Number of received responses.
    • NumPendingRequests - Number of sent requests, which responses are not received yet.
    • BasicServerStats with statistics: TotalRequestsReceived - Number of received requests.
    • TotalResponsesSent - Number of sent responses.
    • NumProcessingRequests - Number of received requests which are not processed yet.
    • TotalErrorResponsesReceivedStats with statistics: TotalErrorResponsesReceived - Number of received error responses.
    • TotalErrorResponsesSentStats with statistics: TotalErrorResponsesSent - Number of sent error responses.
    • TotalRequestProcessingTimeStats with statistics: TotalRequestProcessingTime - Total request processing time.
    • TotalResponseWaitingTimeStats with statistics: TotalResponseWaitingTime - Total response waiting time.
  • DelimitedTextResponseGenerator has been enhanced to recognize the \r\n in the configuration attribute to signify carriage return linefeed.
  • HttpClientConnector has been modified to gzip the request if the Content-Encoding header is set to gzip, using the RequestHeaderMap configuration attribute. 
  • The new FileContentProvider and FileContentWriter components have been added under SoapHttpRequest, to facilitate read/write from/to files directly.
  • The new MessageGenerationBufferSize configuration attribute has been added to SoapHttpRequest, to initialize the internal buffer ahead of time, and avoid frequent copies during buffer expansion.

Collector Components

  • The new MaxMessageLength configuration attribute has been added to SyslogFormatter to allow larger messages (greater than 1024 bytes) to be logged.
  • If the FileNameTZ attribute under FileNamingPolicy is configured with the system, the file name generated will contain the system-specific time zone in it.
  • The PreProcessFileRollPolicy documentation now includes a description concerning the script that maintains the information about the processed file.

Encapsulator Components

  • JDBCEncapsulator has been fixed to pass the Filter value to JDBCTimestampTailingPolicy or JDBCSeqnumTailingPolicy if configured.
  • The PatternDirectoryPolicy has been enhanced with the new SubDirPattern configuration attribute, which can be configured to inspect sub-directories for new files.
  • GTPpSource has been enhanced to receive GTPp requests from multiple IP addresses.
  • UDPEncapsulator can now populate the UDP source IP, source port, destination IP, and destination port. The new configuration attributes SrcAddressAttribute, SrcPortAttribute, ReceivedAddressAttribute, ReceivedPortAttribute, and BindAddress have been added to accomplish this.
  • The new CacheFileList attribute has been added to SFTPSource to support caching large file listings. If set to true, FTP listing files have to be cached for the following operations: fileExists, lastModified, isFile, isDirectory, and length. Otherwise, this attribute is set to false by default. If the number of files in the source directory exceeds 1000, it is recommended to set this attribute to true.

RuleChain Components

  • Collector templates included with the product previously did not have options to configure rulechains in the eIUM Studio wizard or Operations Console. To make rulechains configurable in the included eIUM product templates, re-export the templates with the LaunchPad.
  • Although it had been possible to configure multiple conditional flows with LocalRuleChainInvoker rules having a different static RuleChain configuration attribute, support is now included for an NME attribute with the name of the rule chain to be invoked, thus enabling dynamic configuration of LocalRuleChainInvoker. LocalRuleChainInvoker's RuleChain attribute now supports specifying the NME attribute with the following syntax: %nme_attribute%. The value of the specified NME attribute will be a name of the rule chain to be invoked by LocalRuleChainInvoker. There is a limitation, however, that such a configuration can be used only when UseRuleChainManagerPool=true, which means that no new instance of the invoked rule chain is to be created.

Rule Components

  • The new TimerExecutor component allows scheduling rule execution in a flexible configuration manner. Also see the new TimerRule component, which can create, update, delete or fetch timers. This rule can have a common configuration with the TimerExecutor connector.
  • The new ApplicationIdAttribute and CommandCodeAttribute configuration attributes have been added in DiameterRequestRule and DiameterAnswerRule. They specify NME attributes that contain the outgoing message Application ID and Command Code, respectively.
  • Now each script can be compiled only once by setting the new CacheCompiled ScriptingRule attribute. CacheCompiled is set by default to true for the Groovy scripting engine, and false for the MVEL scripting engine. Requests to compile an already compiled script will be served by creating a copy of the already compiled script. As a result, this will improve eIUM server start-up time.
  • You can now define re-usable functions in a script file, and use (invoke) these functions from in-line script code (defined in the ScriptingRule's ScriptCode attribute).
  • The scripting API now can turn on thread safety for concurrent script execution. The ScriptingRule now has the ThreadSafe Boolean attribute which turns on thread safety.
  • The new AndCondition, OrCondition, and NotCondition components have been added to perform AND/OR operations.
  • The SplitArrayRule SplitAttribute configuration attribute can now be configured with an SNME attribute that is of the primitive array type (such as boolean[], byte[], short[], int[], long[], char[], double[], float[] or string[]) in the SNME Schema.
  • The new NmeSnmeSeparatorCharacter configuration attribute has been added to LogNMERule. The attribute can take any string, escape sequences, or Unicode values, which will be used as separator characters between NME and SNME during logging.
  • Two new operations are introduced in ConditionalRule: 1) "containsAll" checks that a list NME attribute contains all elements of another list NME attribute; and 2) "!containsAll" checks that a list NME attribute does not contain some elements of another list NME attribute. The same operations could be used in FilterRule, ConditionFlushTester, SwitchConditionRule, and NMEAttributeValidationPostProcessor. 
  • In TimeAdornmentRule, the new AdjustmentForDST configuration attribute has been added, which when set to 60, adds an hour to ShiftTime during DST end, and deducts one hour during DST beginning. This will add 25 hours instead of 24 hours during DST end, compensating for the extra hour gained.
  • The new VoltDBStoredProcRule represents a rule to invoke VoltDB Stored Procedures. VoltDB is a newer clustered RDBMS, which provides two methods of accessing the API: JDBC, while the other is through the VoltDB Client API. In eIUM, there have already been rules that could be invoked through JDBC, however, there have not been rules to invoke through the VoltDB Client API. Moreover, JDBC performance can be poor compared to that of using the VoltDB Client API. Consequently, the VoltDBStoredProcRule allows integrating the VoltDB Client API, to support performance sensitive application usage. See the eIUM Component Reference for configuration examples.
  • StringTokenizerRule has been enhanced to support multi-characters as a delimiter to tokenize the input string. It also now handles an empty token value. The new UseRegexDelimiter configuration attribute has been added to StringTokenizerRule, which when set to true, provides both the features of a multi-character delimiter and handling empty tokens.
  • The WriteToFileRule supports SNMEs, along with Base64 decoding, while writing to a file.
  • The ReadFromFileRule supports SNMEs, along with Base64 encoding, while reading a file.
  • The JDBCLookupOperation, JNDILookupOperation, and JNDILookupConnector components have been enhanced in order to support operating directly on SNMEs. The new SNMEType and InputSNMEAttribute configuration attributes have been added. InputSNMEAttribute specifies a SNME attribute under the SNMEType, that will be considered as the root SNME for the current operation. All SNME attributes referred must be relative to this root.
  • The new ConditionalTableRule allows specifying complex conditions where multiple input NME attributes can be evaluated at once and in accordance with the evaluation result of different values that can be assigned to output NME attributes. This component includes "Decision Table" technology, which can be used as a part of business logic implemented via eIUM rule chains. For more information on conditional tables, see the eIUM Overview Guide.
  • SendAlarmRule has been enhanced to handle static and dynamic configuration values.

File Service Workflow

  • To optimize memory usage, the new ScriptCache attribute in WorkflowExecutor configuration allows enabling a script cache, so that compiled scripts will be reused across multiple workflow executions, instead of being compiled multiple times. Though with the cache the memory footprint becomes larger, the performance and memory usage are greatly improved.

Common Codec Framework

  • Now in the XFD file, you can import the namespace defined in another XFD file, and refer to types from that namespace. For instance, if the XFD describes an XML format which includes types defined in different XML namespaces, then it is possible to define one XFD per one XML namespace, and then import those XFDs and refer to types from them, instead of putting all the types into a single namespace and introduce potential name collisions.
  • The CCF XML codec now supports parsing XML which contains repeatable tags with simple content and attributes: 
    <elements>
    <element id="1" type="A">alpha</element>
    <element id="2" type="B">beta</element>
    ...
<elements>
  • CCF includes the JSON codec. The JSON codec supports all features from the eIUM 8.3 Feature Pack 1 release.
  • TLV codec enhancements:
    • Multiple numeric tag values can be specified in a single tag attribute, for an XFD field that uses the CCF TLV codec.
    • For individual fields it is possible to specify a constant length value.
    • Support added for fixed length fields - for the tag-value codec, the user can define a length for a field just in place.
    • Support added for composite tags - a tag can contain more than one field, and a combination of these fields would identify the tag.
  • A new ASN.1 to XFD converter tool has been implemented to convert ASN.1 descriptors to XFD. The xfdtool asn2xfd command allows creating XFD files from given ASN.1 files.
  • JSON has been added to/from the serialization framework, and a generic serialization API has been added. This new framework provides functionality to serialize SNME to JSON, and deserialize SNME from JSON. The framework is used with the LogNMERule and the new SerializerRule rule components, and inside transformations with the new BeanToJson and JsonToBean transformers. The LogNMERule has been enhanced to add logging in JSON format, plus Umbrella SNME support. Furthermore, the SerializerRule can serialize/deserialize NMEs using any available serializer.

Operations Console

  • Performance management/Group KPI - Using this feature it is now possible to calculate group statistics. This allows aggregating statistics for a group of servers. First of all, the Operations Console user should create a new group of servers, and then the management server will aggregate all similar statistics, and using additional statistics providers. For more information, see the eIUM Overview Guide.
  • Multiple alarms can now be acknowledged and cleared simultaneously in the Operations Console. For example, on the Alarms panel for a process, you can select particular alarms using check boxes, and acknowledge or clear them using the context menu selection "Ack/Clear Selected", respectively. Along with selected alarms, you can also acknowledge or clear all alarms using the corresponding context menu selection "Ack/Clear All".
  • Summarized statistics for a group of servers are now provided (accessed via the Custom Group Deployment panel), and are now available in a new Resources panel for a server group.

Reference Data Manager

  • An updated Reference Data Manager web application interface is now available, as part of the new eIUM Web Console, which is a new container to co-locate all eIUM web applications. Web applications (such as the Operations Console, RDM, Tracing) are now grouped together, and the user can switch between them via the main menu. For more information on RDM, see the eIUM Administrator's Guide.

JDBCConnectionPoolService

  • The JDBCLookupOperation, JDBCStoredProcOperation, JDBCUpdateOperation, and VoltDBStoredProcOperationEnhanced JDBC operation components now provide SNME support.

Partition Service

  • The Partition Service is a new feature which provides support for partitioned solutions, where data and services can be logically and physically grouped and those groups can be changed dynamically at runtime. The Partition Service is exposed via the following new components:

    • DistributedPeerNode
    • PartitionModelDatabaseStore
    • PartitionModelHAStore
    • ClientPartitionService
    • PartitionRule
    • LookupOwnPartitionsRule
    • SequenceGeneratorRule

    The Partition Service also includes the new parititonmanager command-line tool. Using the above components, the Partition Service can be configured as a distributed system with High Availability support, where session servers with DistributedPeerNode connectors play a partition application holder role, and any other session servers with the ClientPartitionService and partition-specific rules play a partition application consumers role. By design, the partition application can be changed at runtime using the partitionmanager command-line tool, and those changes would be applied to all clients simultaneously without a need to restart any processes.

Tracing Framework

  • To support tracing and tracking of records in eIUM, the new components TracingRule, TracingService, and TracingManager have been created. The framework takes snapshots of a record at various configured locations, and stores them in a database for visualization in a new web-based graphical interface, eIUM Tracing. The points of interest should be configured with tracing points in the configuration ahead of time. The web-based tracing console allows users to see all the tracing points available in the system and turn them on or off to start recording data. See the Tracing chapter in the eIUM Foundation Guide, as well as the Tracing category of components in the eIUM Component Reference.

eIUM Commands

  • The new secldapcontrol command can add/remove/list the existing partitions in the ApacheDS and OpenLDAP servers.
  • iumconsole documentation has been added to the eIUM Command Reference.
  • The secactivate host command has been enhanced to accept identities under a single argument. New usage is: secactivate host -add -identities "configsvr,management:MgmtServer,opsconsole,reporting,auditreports,rdm,rtp:SNAPStudio".
  • The new statdump tool can dump statistics collected by the central management server, while the statdump audit command allows creating an audit report.
  • The new secserveractivate init argument "krblogincfg" has been added, which will be used only if the "krb" option is set. The Kerberos configuration file path can be specified under this argument, which will be used for Kerberos authentication. If "krblogincfg" is specified, kdchost, kdcport, and dr will be ignored. If "krblogincfg" is not specified, kdchost, kdcport, and dr will be used to create the Kerberos login file.
  • secserveractivate has been enhanced with following new arguments. For Login server: "loginldapts" , "loginldaptspwd" , "loginldaptstype", "loginldaptsprovider"; while for Lookup server: "lookupldapts" , "lookupldaptspwd" , "lookupldaptstype" , "lookupldaptsprovider". These will only be used if "loginldapserver" or "lookupldapserver" URLs are ldaps (LDAP over SSL) connections. 
  • It is now possible to use processmanager to remove a process from the configuration using a single invocation of the new delete command. processmanager also now supports all siucontrol command functions.
  • The new command secactivate webapp has been created to handle secure, unsecure, and update HTTPS for web applications in eIUM. See the new arguments "-secure", "-unsecure", and "-httpsupdate".
  • The former vnfmsecactivate utility has been removed and its functions have instead been ported to secactivate. Securing/unsecuring Cloud Interconnect Server components can be done using the secactivate cis command and additional parameters, as required.
  • The new msdump tool has been added (which contains load and save commands), to support management server data migration (export and import functions). This tool can export/import the following configurations from a running management server: group of servers; operations in the scheduler; measurement jobs; threshold monitors; derived attributes; and configuration of group statistics providers.

eIUM Studio, ConfigEditor, & Deployment Manager

  • The copy/paste functions in the ConfigEditor Outline have been improved to copy-paste between different editors. Accordingly, eIUM Studio users can now copy nodes in one editor and insert them into another editor.
  • It is now possible to specify a commit message when loading configurations to the eIUM configuration server.
  • A new Pin option has been added the to JMX view menu. In pin mode, the JMX view will not change its contents when a selection in the Deployment tree is changed. The maximum number of opened JMX views is configurable in Window -> Preferences -> Deployment Manager.
  • Linked nodes can be shown in the Outline by selecting Show linked nodes in the Outline menu. To edit a linked node with the Outline, you should select a linked node in the Outline tree and choose "Overwrite node" from right-click menu, to uncomment the linked node, or "Reset node" to use the default linked node configuration and the linked node will be commented. The ConfigEditor also provides hot-keys CTRL+# (CTRL+SHIFT+3) to comment/uncomment a linked configuration.
  • The new File HDFS Copy Task has been added. This new task is another copy task variant, which can copy files to an HDFS file system. The task uses the webhdfs scheme for non-secure transfer, and swebhdfs for a secure connection to the HDFS. The URL takes the following format: webhdfs://<ip>: <port>/.
  • The new annotation @Import(path="path to a template in the repository", node="note to merge") is available. The node argument is optional. If it is not defined, the full template will be merged into the current node). After deploying such a template, all imported templates will be merged into a single one and copied to the main configuration.
  • A conditional table can now be created by right-clicking in the Project explorer view, and selecting New -> New Conditional Table.
  • When the user performs the "restart with cleanup" operation from the Deployment Manager of eIUM Studio, there will now first be a confirmation pop-up window, and once it is submitted, the operation proceeds and completes without any further interaction from the user.
  • Added the Properties option to the right-click menu for all Deployment Manager processes. This launches the Properties view and displays properties for the selected process. A Host default properties option has also been added to the right-click menu for hosts which launch the Properties view with the active tab "Default" for the selected host.

Cloud Interconnect Server (CIS)

  • The former VNF Manager feature is now referred to as Cloud Interconnect Server in the eIUM product. Its documentation has also been moved from the eIUM Foundation Guide to the new eIUM Virtualization Guide. The former vnftools command line utility has also been renamed as the new cistools utility. See the eIUM Command Reference for more information.
  • Cloud Interconnect Server uses an execution engine based on the industry-adopted Apache Ant toolkit. The VNF Descriptor is an input to the CIS execution engine. The VNF Descriptor is very flexible and allows the end user to use the standard Ant task library or even write new custom tasks and use them as part of the CIS extension. To increase flexibility even more as part of this release, support for the Groovy scripting language has been added to the VNF Descriptor. Customers will be able to provide an external Groovy script or execute in-line Groovy scripts in the VNF Descriptor. This will enhance the user experience and provide more flexibility in configuring VNFs.
  • VNF scoped context has been implemented, to provide a place to store VNF scoped data. VNF components can use this context to share information. Typically, VNF consists of one or more components. VNF components are specified in a VNF Descriptor, and can be instantiated in a user-defined order. This allows the end-user to sequence VNFC instantiation. Sometimes, however, there are more complex dependencies between VNF Components, for example, they need to be aware of each other as the business mission requires them to cooperate, they need to expose and share their state, expose IP address, and so on. For such cases, Cloud Interconnect Server provides the VNF Context, which can be accessed for read and write by all VNF Components constituting the VNF. The use-case for the sharing state is fulfilled in such a way, that one of the VNFC writes data to mutually known location in the VNF Context, and the other VNF Components read it. There is a dedicated Ant task for writing and reading VNF Context. For <cache method="write|read" key="KEY_NAME" property="PROPERTY_NAME"/>:
    • method - Allowed values: read or write, in case of "read", it loads the VNF Context value located under the value specified, as the key into an Ant project property specified by the property. For "write", it saves the value of the Ant project property, specified by the property value into the VNF Context under the key specified by the key parameter.
    • key - The key name in the VNF Context, under which the value is located or to be saved.
    • property - The Ant project property name, either to store the VNF Context value, or in case of "write", to be the source of the VNF Context value.
  • Cloud Interconnect Server has been extended to support High Availability setup. A dedicated set of tools have been added to manage CIS instances in an HA setup. For more information, see the eIUM Virtualization User Guide.
  • From eIUM 9.0, integration with VNFs instantiated by VNFM from eIUM83 Feature Pack 1 is supported. Apart from the cistools vnfdmigrate command for VNFD migration to version 2, there is a new vdd command in for import and export details about instantiated VNFs.
  • During eIUM activation it is now possible to specify whether the embedded MySQL database or some other external database should be used by Cloud Interconnect Server for persisting its data.
  • All VNF life-cycle operations were switched to asynchronous (non-blocking) mode.
    • The Or-Vnfm API has been reworked to comply with the latest finalized ETSI MANO Specification and Information Model (ETSI GS NFV-IFA 007 V2.1.1 (2016-10) Network Functions Virtualization (NFV); Management and Orchestration; Or-Vnfm reference point - Interface and Information Model Specification). All long running operations, mostly Lifecycle Operations, have been switched to asynchronous mode. Custom extensions of the Or-Vnfm interface have been migrated from the previous version with improvements in input/output message structures. The eIUM EMS plug-in has been extended with functionality to manage Threshold Monitors and retrieve eIUM component statuses.
    • The Apache Ant-based Execution Engine has been updated with a new pluggable and extensible mechanism for custom ANT plug-ins. This approach allows developing and adding new ANT plug-ins by third party vendors for integration with 3rd party VNFs.
    • VDU types have been extended with an extensible mechanism that allows third party vendors to develop and provide third party VNF-specific KPI and Alarm managing plug-ins.
    • VNF Descriptor Model Extensions - Integration of external components as new type of VDUs:
      • Allows seamlessly integrating third-party components or entire VNFs into the standard model.
      • Allows leveraging the full range of existing capabilities on unknown elements Integration of custom tasks into the standard or extended life cycle.
      • In addition to the wide range of standard tasks, new VNFM-specific tasks could be developed to interact and control third-party components.
      • New tasks could be used in the context of the standard or custom targets and could be combined with the standard tasks.
    • Integration of custom KPIs providers via new KPI provider types - New KPI providers can be developed to collect (poll or push) extended KPIs at the VDU level.
  • The Cloud Interconnect Server (CIS) user interface is a web-based application designed for CIS operators who need to monitor and manage VNF Instances on a daily basis. It builds on top of the CIS REST API and command-line interface tools to streamline the user experience. The CIS web application uses the eIUM web framework, providing a similar look and feel as other modern web applications on the eIUM platform. For more information, see the eIUM Overview Guide or Virtualization User Guide.

Configuration Server and Repository Server

  • In this release, the former Repository Server process has been removed, and instead the repository is now based on Git. The eIUM repository now resides within the Configuration Server. To work with the repository content, you can use the repositorymanager command utility, or eIUM Studio (as previously), but additionally you can also use any Git client of choice. To clone the repository content run the following: git clone http(s)://repository-host:repository-port/repositoryserver/server.
  • eIUM includes a configuration versioning capability, namely, the history of changes, diffs, reverting, switching to another version, and so on. The eIUM configuration is split into two configurations: versioned and non-versioned. The versioned configuration is stored in the repository as a text file (/RepositoryServer/configs/deployment.config), while the non-versioned configuration is stored in a database. For more information, see the eIUM Overview Guide and eIUM Studio User Guide.
  • High Availability (HA) support is now available. Multiple instances of the configuration server and repository server are now supported. If one instance is down, eIUM processes are automatically switched to another.

Management Server

  • The management server can now send an alarm when a predefined throughput limit is reached.

Real-Time Engine

  • Deployment changes - The following Real-Time Engine deployment models are no longer supported:
    • IMDB-based deployments and N+1 deployments - DDC is not supported anymore, and therefore all IMDB-based deployment scenarios and N+1 deployment models are no longer supported. The IMDB is a DDC provider for in-memory database. For more information about Real-Time Engine deployments, see the eIUM Overview Guide.
  • Assetstore - Added the -N command to specify the existing Studio Session Server name in an assetstore tool command line.
  • Decision Table functionality now supports manual debug performance in the graphical user interface. Queries can be executed, for example, 100 times and return the maximum, minimum, and average time as a measure to the user about how well the Decision Table design is performing.
    • The Decision Table feature also supports IPV6 regular expressions. The new IPv6RegExp data type was added to support IPV6 regular expressions.
  • Regular expressions and longestStringMatch, specified for matching String input parameters in Decision Tables, are now supported. For example: (1) String Lists: rexp:A0202|B0101|C0230; (2) Not like: rexp:^(?!(AB)).*; and (3) Not: rexp:^(?!P00123$).*$. Examples of longestStringMatch: (1) longestStringMatch ‘12345’ -> corresponds to 12345, 1234512, 123452345, 12345901, etc.; and (2) longestStringMatch ‘123457’ -> corresponds to 123457, 1234570, 123457923, 12345716, etc.
  • The new InvokeDecisionTableRule component has been added for invoking the Decision Table. 

Real-Time Engine Studios

  • Business logic - The following entities are no longer supported and therefore they are no longer available in the Real-Time Studio (SNAP Studio):
    • Entities in Business View - The following entities in the Business View of the Real-Time Studio are no longer supported:
      • CDR Generation - Since the Real-Time Engine generates CDRs using the IUM CDR mechanism, there is no need to configure the CDR generation rules in the Real-Time Engine.
      • Rule Flow - The real-time business rules now only support business rule (Guided editor), DRL rule (technical rule-text editor), and decision table data. Rule flow is no longer supported.
      • Decision Tree
      • Action
    • Technical View and all entities under it - The Technical View has been removed from the Real-Time Studio and therefore all entities under it are no longer supported, including:
      • Application
      • Rule Global Configuration
      • Service Configuration
      • Lookup Configuration
      • Workflow Configuration
      • Rule
      • Workflow
      • RDS
    • The Technical View and the entities under it can still be enabled for developers. For detailed instructions, see the eIUM Real-Time Engine Developer Guide.
    • In addition to the above changes,the following enhancements regarding the real-time business logic are done in this release:
      • Enhanced decision table to support the IPv6 regular expression.
      • Enhanced message catalog to support message internationalization.
  • A new SNAP administrative studio for subscription, quota, and counter data provisioning from SPR is available. Users can buy products on the subscriber or device. After the subscription is created, the quota usage and counter will display in the subscription page.
  • The session viewer, KPI monitoring, history manager, and subscriber trace (old OMC Log) have been removed from the Studio and have been moved to the Operations Console in the RTC extension.
  • Account Balance Management has been added in the SPR studio. Users can create/close/remove an Account, Account Balance, Balances Share Rule, and Account Relationship. Users can also recharge/refund/adjust the account balance.
  • Users can create a subscriber and their device information simultaneously in SPR Admin Studio. In addition, users can update subscriber or device configuration after searching by device identifier type and value.

Load Balancer

  • The Load Balancer provides the new ThroughputLimitationAlgorithm component, which can throttle the request throughput to a back-end server, according to a user-specified throttle threshold.
  • To enable the Load Balancer to support front-end load balancing, it introduces a new AssociateConnectorName attribute for the BackEndServerGroup component. For a back-end group which is slated for front-end load balancing, the user needs to configure the AssociateConnectorName, and specify the inbound connector name for it. The front-end load balancing is similar to normal load balancing, and it depends on the configured algorithm for the corresponding back-end server group.
  • The Real-Time Engine Load Balancer is no longer used, replaced by the eIUM Load Balancer. For details on how to configure an eIUM Load Balancer, see the eIUM Load Balancer Guide. The introduction of the eIUM Load Balancer brings the following changes to the Real-Time Engine:
    • Connectors - All previous Real-Time Engine connectors are no longer supported, replaced by IUM connectors.
    • SPI adapters - All SPI adapters are no longer needed, as now the Real-Time Engine uses IUM connectors to communicate with the network directly.
  • Support for automatic disabling of back-end server by a predefined error rate threshold, according to the captured error response:
    • The Load Balancer can capture the error rate of the response coming from the back-end server. It can automatically disable the back-end server which reached the predefined error rate threshold and send an alarm to notify the user.
    • See the new LBErrorRateAggStatisticHandler, ThresholdOption, and ErrorRatePolicy components.
  • Single connector load balancing:
    • Support for load balancing with one connector.
    • See the LoadbalancerRouter new SingleConnector attribute.
  • NMELink protocol support:
    • The Load Balancer now integrates with the new NMELinkConnector, thereby supporting the NMELink protocol.
  • Dynamically persisting connection support for back-end server:
    • The Load Balancer now supports dynamically adding a Diameter back-end server into the persistent connection list, for instance, if the connection between the Load Balancer and back-end server was broken. The Load Balancer can as a result be immediately aware and rebuild the connection in a timely manner.
    • See the BackendServer component, where a third new configuration example has been added to show how to configure a back-end server address as a persistent connection.
  • Back-end server traffic throttling:
    • The Load Balancer now includes the new ThroughputLimitationAlgorithm component, which allows throttling the throughput to back-end servers.
    • See the new ThroughputLimitationAlgorithm component, as well as the pre-existing NMDecisionAlgorithm and RuleChainAlgorithm components for more information.
  • ParitionService integration:
    • The Load Balancer includes a new algorithm component, PartitionAlgorithm, which allows the Load Balancer to seamlessly integrate with the new PartitionSerivce.
  • Front-end load balancing:
    • The Load Balancer now supports load balancing requests originating from back-end servers.
    • See the BackendServerGroup component's two new related attributes: EagerlyConnect and AssociateConnectorName.

Installation and Activation

  • A new installer is provided for eIUM 9.0. It uses the same new framework as the eIUM Activation Wizard. This framework is based on eIUM's own rulechain workflow execution. For more information, see the eIUM Installation Guide.
  • It is now always required to run an eIUM installation as the root user on UNIX/Linux. If it is desired to run eIUM as the non-root user, this must be specified during installation. The installer will set all permissions and ownership correctly and start the activation as the required user. The eIUM uninstaller must be also run as root. Nonroot scripts (nonrootpre.sh and nonrootunprep.sh) should NO LONGER be used.
  • New start-up scripts have been implemented. The Windows scripts are implemented in PowerShell, thus the PowerShell interpreter is required to be installed on the system. The Windows service is installed/removed by the activator. The service is quite simple: on start-up, it executes the Powershell script with the start option, and on shutdown it executes the Powershell script with the stop option. Start-up scripts are the following:
    • Linux: run /etc/init.d/SIU -h for usage details: $ /etc/init.d/SIU_90 -h Usage: SIU_90 [start [module]] [stop [module]] [restart [module]] [status [module]] Modules: agent cis dbs license
    • Windows: run c:\SIU\sbin\SIU.bat -h for usage details: > c:\SIU\sbin\SIU.bat Usage: [start [module]] [stop [module]] [restart [module]] [status [module]]
    • The main eIUM service script (/etc/init.d/SIU) allows option bundles (formerly "product extensions"), such as the License Server, to plug in their own services. It is now possible to start/stop/restart all installed and enabled services by running /etc/init.d/SIU {start|stop|restart}. It is also possible to start/stop/restart individual services by running commands like /etc/init.d/SIU license_start. When called without parameters, /etc/init.d/SIU will provide some information on available options and enabled services.
  • The eIUM Activation Wizard has been re-factored to use eIUM's own powerful rule chain capabilities, to build a configurable activation/deactivation work flow of standard and specialized components. It also allows plugging in additional activation modules by providing configuration files.
  • The eIUM Activation Wizard has been enhanced to provide Security Server activation if the Security Server option bundle is installed during installation. Additionally, the activator has been enhanced to activate security for eIUM. This feature allows activating security at the time of activation only. In addition, the secserveractivate and secactivate commands have been enhanced for a better user experience.
  • The installer and activator can now be made to write a transcript of the user's parameter choices. This transcript can be used later as a "response file" for silent-mode installation or activation. Values for password parameters will be encrypted in such a transcript file, unless -A EncryptResponses=false is provided. By default, encryption will be performed using the eIUM built-in keystore, so that silent-mode installation or activation will be able to automatically decrypt the file. The user could also provide an optional password for transcript file encryption, so that silent-mode installation/activation will only be able to use this file if the same password will be provided. For the installer, the corresponding options are:
    • -w <file> (to write the transcript file)
    • -w <file> -A OutputResponseFilePassword=<password> (to encrypt the file with target password)
    • -i silent -f <file> (to perform silent-mode install using <file> as the response file)
    • -i silent -f <file> -respFilePassword <password> (the same with password)

    If the installer is prepended with -w, then the corresponding options will also be passed to the activator, including the transcript file name and password. The activator's transcript will be appended to the same file. The additional option -sampleRespFile <file> was provided to the installer, to write a template response file with all available installation parameters to <file>. The corresponding command line for the activator is ./activator samplerespfile -o <file>.

  • Parameter values can now be provided directly on the command line during activation/installation. As a result, specific parameters from a silent response file can be overridden. Even in interactive mode, initial values for parameters could be provided (for example, when helping someone to set up a system remotely). The new -P (or, -parameter) option was added to the activate/deactivate commands, as well as the installer/uninstaller. Example usage: ./activate silent -f install.opt -P REPOSITORYPORT=18300.
  • With the new eIUM License Server, customers are free to decide where to deploy eIUM configuration servers (the eIUM license will allow deploying configuration servers on any host). All configuration servers will connect to this licensing service to obtain run permission (namely, a license token). Licenses can also be added to, as well as deleted from, the License Server. For more information, see the eIUM Installation Guide.

eIUM System

  • Hadoop/HDFS integration in eIUM is exposed as the new FileManagerDelivery and FileManagerSource components, the new BPMN2 worfklow HDFS File Copy Task, as well as JDS integration in terms of the webhdfs scheme name. For more information, see the eIUM Component Reference and eIUM Foundation Guide.
  • The Security Server itself has been enhanced and now includes an embedded LDAP (ApacheDS) server in the product. As the Security Server is not required on every eIUM host, the customer may want to avoid installing this additional software. As a result, the Security Server is now provided as a separate but additional option bundle. This bundle requires no specific license, so it could be installed on every Standard or Bare eIUM host. Installation on Client hosts is prohibited and inapplicable. When selecting embedded mode in installation, ApacheDS will also automatically start when eIUM starts.
  • The new ExternalDirectoryLoginModule login module has been implemented to search and bind a user identity.
  • eIUM now supports MySQL 5.7.17.
  • The enterprise ID has been changed, and the product now uses a new IANA number for HPE. Previously this number was: iso(1) org(3) dod(6) internet(1) private(4) enterprises(1) hp(11) nm(2) ium (27). The new number is: iso(1) org(3) dod(6) internet(1) private(4) enterprises(1) hpe(47196) nm(2) hpeCMS (1) hpeeIUM(1).
  • You can customize the MIB by changing the product ID. For example, if there are two different products based on eIUM, and you would like to distinguish them, you can define a different product ID using the new ProductID attribute in the SnmpAgent configuration.
  • VoltDB version 6.4 is now supported.
  • You can now control security permissions access to the eIUM configuration trees via the following new policy file: %VARROOT%/ConfigServer/security-policy.xml. This file allows granting permissions to configuration trees. See the eIUM Overview Guide for more information. The new configuration file "security.properties" has also been created under the %VARROOT%/securityserver/conf/ directory. This contains the default values for all the security parameters. If this file does not contain any security parameter (missing parameter), then the old default properties will be used.

eIUM Documentation

  • The eIUM Command Reference now includes a command index page. To access this, click Command Index at the top of the Command Reference navigation tree.

As an HPE customer, you can obtain the most current software releases and documentation by contacting your HPE Sales representative or HPE Delivery contact. Or, you can open a support case by e-mail to request assistance: iumsupport@hpe.com.

Resolution:

The installer and activator can now be made to write a transcript of the user's parameter choices. This transcript can be used later as a "response file" for silent-mode installation or activation. Values for password parameters will be encrypted in such a transcript file unless -A EncryptResponses=false is provided. By default, encryption will be performed using the eIUM built-in keystore, so that silent-mode installation or activation will be able to automatically decrypt the file. For the installer, the corresponding options are:

  -w <file> (to write the transcript file)

  -i silent -f <file> (to perform silent-mode install using <file> as the response file)
  -i silent -f <file> -respFilePassword <password> (the same with password)

If the installer is prepended with "-w", then the corresponding options will also be passed to the activator, including the transcript file name and password. The activator's transcript will be appended to the same file. The additional option "-sampleRespFile <file>" was provided to the installer, to write a template response file with all available installation parameters to <file>. The corresponding command line for the activator is "./activator samplerespfile -o <file>".

ID: QXCR1001541996

State: Awaiting Release

Visibility: Lab only

Engineer: Stepien,Sylwester (Everett) [sstepien@hpe.com]

Symptoms:

CIS and webappserver startup time takes longer than expected.

Resolution:

Long startup time of CIS and webappserver is correlated with the time needed to scan libraries present on the classpath. Jar libraries are scanned to discover portable artefacts (Servlet 3.0 feature) such as web fragments, discover annotated web components, etc. The issue was that too many libraries were scanned. The idea behind custom scanner is that only libraries listed in context file are scanned, this limits scan to only a few and improves startup time on average by 50%.

Test Info Notes:

On average startup time of CIS and webappserver should be faster by 50%. Beside that no other changes in functionality or any side-effects should be observed.

Verifier: 

Verified by : Penumathsa Chaitanya Varma
Release     : eIUM90
Verified in : RC7 
Branch      : next-tissot
TET Status  : Need to automate/automated

In this Build, the startup of CIS & Webappserver is faster by 50%.

Operating System Name: Linux
Operating System Version: 3.10.0-514.6.1.el7.x86_64

It was verified that with following configuration in server/client:

ServerIP=16.53.146.255
ServerIP=10.10.1.1
ServerIP=127.0.0.1

CER/CEA messages contain following set of Host-IP-Address (257) AVPs:

00 00 01 01 40 00 00 0e 00 01 10 35 92 ff 00 00 
00 00 01 01 40 00 00 0e 00 01 0a 0a 01 01 00 00 
00 00 01 01 40 00 00 0e 00 01 7f 00 00 01 00 00

So proper info is encoded, AVP code (101 in HEX means 257) and values with "00 01" prefix means IPv4
and further HEX coded IP address from ServerIP conf attribute values.

ID: QXCR1001539504

State: Awaiting Release

Visibility: Lab, Support & Customer

Engineer: Chernyavsky,Ivan [chernyavsky@hpe.com]

Content Reviewed?: Y

Symptoms:

When installing eIUM on Unix/Linux, it should be possible to request non-root installation directly from the Installer GUI/CLI, without performing any steps in advance (such as running nonrootprep.sh).

Resolution:

It is now ALWAYS required to run an eIUM installation as the root user on Unix/Linux. If it is desired to run eIUM as the non-root user, this must be specified during installation. The installer will set all permissions and ownership correctly and start the activation as the required user. The eIUM uninstaller must be also run as root. Nonroot scripts (nonrootpre.sh and nonrootunprep.sh) should NO LONGER be used.

Submitter Text Notes:

When installing IUM on Unix/Linux, it should be possible to request non-root installation directly from Installer GUI/CLI, without performing any steps in advance (such as running nonrootprep.sh).

Test Info Notes:

Please ensure that:

- IUM installer will allow to provide non-root <user> to run IUM (for silent mode, use NONROOT_INSTALL=true and INSTANCEOWNER=<user>) - Installation performed this way will lead to IUM instance with correct ownership (<user>:bin) - IUM instance will be functional (i.e. basic sanity tests like start/stop/launchpad/demo collector creation/IUMStudio) - Uninstallation of such instance (run by user root!) will leave no files except in the SIUHOME/uninstall directory (it should also leave no links in /etc/rc.*)

ID: QXCR1001539233

State: Awaiting Release

Visibility: Lab, Support & Customer

Engineer: Chernyavsky,Ivan [chernyavsky@hpe.com]

Symptoms:

When deactivation fails during uninstallation, the user should explicitly give his consent to continue uninstallation.

In silent mode, this should be confirmed by setting corresponding value in the responses file.

Resolution:

Implemented as an additional screen in uninstall wizard which is only shown if deactivation fails.

The user should check a confirmation checkbox on said screen in order to continue with uninstallation.

In the silent mode, parameter IGNORE_DEACTIVATE_RESULT must be set to "true" either in responses file, or on the command line with -P IGNORE_DEACTIVATE_RESULT=true.

Submitter Text Notes:

When deactivation fails during uninstallation, the user should explicitly give his consent to continue uninstallation.

In silent mode, this should be confirmed by setting corresponding value in the responses file.

Test Info Notes:

Please verify that, for secured IUM deployment:

- during uninstallation, canceling the deactivation or entering wrong password thrice will lead to "Deactivation Failed" screen which will ask the user to explicitly confirm uninstallation - pressing "Cancel" on "Deactivation Failed" screen (or entering ":quit" in console mode) will exit uninstallation without deleting any files - this "Deactivation Failed" screen and confirmation checkbox will not be visible if deactivation is not performed (e.g. host is not activated) or deactivation is successful - in silent mode, if no parameters are provided for uninstallation, deactivation will fail and uninstallation will be aborted after this without deleting any files - in silent mode, providing IGNORE_DEACTIVATE_RESULT=true (either from responses file or using option -P on the command line) will allow to uninstall even after failed deactivation. (IUM services must be still stopped correctly by uninstallation itself.)

In unsecured IUM deployment it's not possible to cancel the deactivation, thus it's only possible to make it fail to test this CR. Easiest way to make it fail is to make you JVM non-JCE-unlimited-strength and start uninstallation without EncryptResponses option:

- deactivation will fail. Make sure the same "Deactivation Failed" screen is shown as above and it's possible to either stop or continue uninstallation at this point.

ID: QXCR1001538964

State: Awaiting Release

Visibility: Lab only

Engineer: Tsoukanov,Victor [victor.tsoukanov@hpe.com]

Submitter Text Notes:

1. RMI server should use port from configured range. 2. RMI server should support listen_port file.

Test Info Notes:

It should be checked for both secured and unsecured instance. It can be checked on session server, collector, admin agent and other IUM process with embedded management service. For AA RmiPort configuration attribute has high priority 1. Create a new demo collector with name 'ds' 2. Start it using launchpad. 3. Check if there a new file SIU\var\ds\listen_rmi_port with port used for RMI server, see log 'RMI connector server created [service:jmx:rmi://host/jndi/rmi://host:XXXX/jmxconnector]' 4. Stop collector. 5. Start collector. It should be bound to port defined in SIU\var\ds\listen_rmi_port. 6. Remove SIU\var\ds\listen_rmi_port 7. Set port range java properties rmi.net.socket_factory.port.min, rmi.net.socket_factory.port.max 8. Start collector. RMI server should be bound to port in range [rmi.net.socket_factory.port.min, rmi.net.socket_factory.port.max]

For secure IUM, one more range should be defined: [rmi.net.ssl_socket_factory.port.min, rmi.net.ssl_socket_factory.port.max]. In RMI it is mandatory to have RMI registry started. In case of unsecured IUM, registry and JMX connector share same port. For secured instance it is not possible - RMI regsitry and connector should be bound to different ports. JMX connector port will be saved in listen_ssl_rmi_port similar to listen_rmi_port

Kafka connector performance enhancement for a single NME (Refer as respose/request mode).

Test Info Notes:

The flow for batch mode and request/response were same. Hence, the request/response mode was having poor throughput. The change is to separate these mode into two flow. While doing this, the throughput has been increased many fold.

ID: QXCR1001536755

State: Completed

Visibility: Lab, Support & Customer

Engineer: Pavlenko,Andrey [andrey.pavlenko@hpe.com]

Content Reviewed?: Y

Symptoms:

Support is needed for startup scripts for Linux and Windows, which can provide identical usage and functionality. Additionally, the Windows scripts must be integrated with Windows services.

Resolution:

New start-up scripts have been implemented. The Windows scripts are implemented in PowerShell, thus the PowerShell interpreter is required to be installed on the system. The Windows service is installed/removed by the activator. The service is quite simple: on start-up, it executes the Powershell script with the start option, and on shutdown it executes the Powershell script with the stop option. Start-up scripts are the following:

Linux: run /etc/init.d/SIU -h for usage details:

$ /etc/init.d/SIU_90 -h Usage: SIU_90 [start [module]] [stop [module]] [restart [module]] [status [module]] Modules: agent cis dbs license

Windows: run c:\SIU\sbin\SIU.bat -h for usage details:

> c:\SIU\sbin\SIU.bat Usage: [start [module]] [stop [module]] [restart [module]] [status [module]]

Submitter Text Notes:

Support is needed for startup scripts for Linux and Windows, which can provide identical usage and functionality. Additionally, the Windows scripts must be integrated with Windows services.

Test Info Notes:

Linux: run /etc/init.d/SIU -h for usage details:

$ /etc/init.d/SIU_90 -h Usage: SIU_90 [start [module]] [stop [module]] [restart [module]] [status [module]] Modules: agent cis dbs license

Windows: run c:\SIU\sbin\SIU.bat -h for usage details:

> c:\SIU\sbin\SIU.bat Usage: [start [module]] [stop [module]] [restart [module]] [status [module]] Modules: agent dbs

ID: QXCR1001535261

State: Awaiting Release

Visibility: Lab only

Engineer: Stepien,Sylwester (Everett) [sstepien@hpe.com]

Symptoms:

Scale In ends up with an error. The VNF is not scaled in.

Resolution:

The issue manifests itself in situation when for example scaleout target has a problem. The end user tries to scale out such VNF, VM is created but then scale operation fails as there is a problem with scaleout target in descriptor. After fixing descriptor and removal of VM the enduser tries to scale out VNF using the same name for VM. This time operation succeeds. However subsequent scale in operation fails with error that target server cannot be found. The issue was the leftover entry in database from the first scaleout try (the one that errored), scale in fails as it try to use that leftover when looking up for a target server.

ID: QXCR1001535244

State: Awaiting Release

Visibility: Lab, Support & Customer

Engineer: Stepien,Sylwester (Everett) [sstepien@hpe.com]

Content Reviewed?: Y

Symptoms:

Support is needed for integrating Groovy with the VNF Descriptor, so it is possible to execute in- line Groovy or external Groovy scripts.

Resolution:

Cloud Interconnect Server uses an execution engine based on the industry-adopted Apache Ant toolkit. The VNF Descriptor is an input to the CIS execution engine. The VNF Descriptor is very flexible and allows the end user to use the standard Ant task library or even write new custom tasks and use them as part of the CIS extension. To increase flexibility even more as part of this release, support for the Groovy scripting language has been added to the VNF Descriptor. Customers will be able to provide an external Groovy script or execute in-line Groovy scripts in the VNF Descriptor. This will enhance the user experience and provide more flexibility in configuring VNFs.

Submitter Text Notes:

Integrate Groovy with VNF Descriptor so it is possible to execute inline groovy or external groovy script.

Following should be possible <target name="groovy.scripting.is.cool"> <groovy> int i = 0 // read numberOfIterations ant script property int numberOfIterations = properties["numberOfIterations"].toInteger() while (i &lt;= numberOfIterations) { //execute custom target 'echo.target' ant.project.executeTarget('echo.target') i++ } </groovy> </target>

or following (executing build.groovy script): <target name="groovy.scripting.is.cool"> <groovy src="/root/scripts/build.groovy"> <arg value="${buildName}"/> <arg value="${basedir}"/> </groovy> </target>

Test Info Notes:

Ensure inline groovy scripting as well as external groovy script are working fine in VNF Descriptor

Example of inline: <target name="echo.target"> <echo message="hello" /> </target> <target name="groovy.scripting.is.cool"> <!-- an example of how to use groovy in ant descriptor --> <groovy> int i = 0 int numberOfIterations = properties["numberOfIterations"].toInteger() while (i &lt;= numberOfIterations) { ant.project.executeTarget('echo.target') i++ } </groovy> </target>

Example of external: <target name="groovy.scripting.is.cool"> <groovy src="/root/scripts/build.groovy"> <arg value="${buildName}"/> <arg value="${basedir}"/> </groovy> </target>

ID: QXCR1001534909

State: Awaiting Release

Visibility: Lab, Support & Customer

Engineer: Stepien,Sylwester (Everett) [sstepien@hpe.com]

Content Reviewed?: Y

Symptoms:

Support is needed for sharing some information between VNF components. For example, components need to be aware of each other to exchange some information, and in such a case they need to know each other's IP addresses.

Resolution:

VNF scoped context has been implemented, to provide a place to store VNF scoped data. VNF components can use this context to share information.

Typically, VNF consists of one or more components. VNF components are specified in a VNF Descriptor, and can be instantiated in a user-defined order. This allows the end-user to sequence VNFC instantiation. Sometimes, however, there are more complex dependencies between VNF Components, for example, they need to be aware of each other as the business mission requires them to cooperate, they need to expose and share their state, expose IP address, and so on. For such cases, Cloud Interconnect Server provides the VNF Context, which can be accessed for read and write by all VNF Components constituting the VNF. The use-case for the sharing state is fulfilled in such a way, that one of the VNFC writes data to mutually known location in the VNF Context, and the other VNF Components read it.

There is a dedicated Ant task for writing and reading VNF Context.

<cache method="write|read" key="KEY_NAME" property="PROPERTY_NAME"/>

method - Allowed values: read or write, in case of "read", it loads the VNF Context value located under the value specified, as the key into an Ant project property specified by the property. For "write", it saves the value of the Ant project property, specified by the property value into the VNF Context under the key specified by the key parameter.

key - The key name in the VNF Context, under which the value is located or to be saved.

property - The Ant project property name, either to store the VNF Context value, or in case of "write", to be the source of the VNF Context value.

Submitter Text Notes:

Implement VNF scoped context so it is accessible via custom ant task at the VNF descriptor level. This requirement is driven by business need to share data between various VNFC within the same VNF.

Following should be possible after implementation: <configure> <!-- set MyProperty1 value to 'foo' --> <property name="MyProperty1" value="foo"/> <!-- persist the value of MyProperty1 in VNF scoped context --> <cache method="write" key="MyKey" property="MyProperty1"/> </configure>

<update> <!-- reinitialize MyProperty2 in the ant project --> <var name="MyProperty2" unset="true"/> <!-- load value from VNF context located under MyKey into MyProperty2 --> <cache method="read" key="MyKey" property="MyProperty2"/> <!-- prints â€œfooâ€ -->. <echo>MyProperty = ${MyProperty2}</echo> </update>

Lifecycle of the VNF Scoped context Context should be initialized on VNF instantiation and destroyed on VNF termination.

Test Info Notes:

1. IN ems VDU configure target put following:

2. In eium host VDU configure target put following:

3. In eium host VDU add following custom target <target name="read.ips"> <!-- an example of how to read from VNF scoped context values that were set in different part of VNF lifecycle --> <cache method="read" key="ems_hostIp" property="ems_hostIp"/> <echo message="ems ip address is: ${ems_hostIp}"/> <cache method="read" key="eium_hostIp" property="eium_hostIp"/> <echo message="eium ip address is: ${eium_hostIp}"/> </target> 3. Instantiate a new VNF

4. Execute read.ips custom target 5. Observe vnfm.log (ensure logging level is set to debug), there should be entries corresponding to <echo> messages from read.ips target

ID: QXCR1001534012

State: Awaiting Release

Visibility: Lab only

Engineer: Chernyavsky,Ivan [chernyavsky@hpe.com]

Submitter Text Notes:

Lists of CLI aliases are currently configured in a global file $SIUHOME/lib/plugincmdaliases. When some of the commands are only available when specific Merge Modules (Additional Components) are installed, it could lead to present but broken CLI commands. Thus it is advisable to provide per-Merge Module lists of aliases along with the global list.

As an extra feature, it was requested by SNAP team to support creation of CLI aliases in random dirs under SIUHOME, e.g. in SIUHOME/UPM/bin.

Test Info Notes:

Please check that all required aliases (including those defined for VNFM and LS in separate files under SIUHOME/lib/plugincmdaliases.d) are created correctly.

On Windows, please check that GUI aliases created (e.g. launchpad) will only show a GUI window, without opening new console windows (meaning they will use javaw.exe instead of java.exe).

If you have nothing to do, you may also want to check the queerest part of it: creation of aliases in arbitrary dirs. To do so, install and activate IUM normally, then stop it and drop a file with following content to SIUHOME/lib/plugincmdaliases.d:

saveconfig cli MYDIR/bin

(the file itself could have whatever name).

Finally, run:

    java -jar /opt/<SIU>/sbin/activateSIUJava.jar /opt/<SIU> -createAliases

This should create directory /opt/<SIU>/MYDIR/bin, your copy of "saveconfig" in this directory as well as a couple of supporting symlinks under /opt/<SIU>/MYDIR.

Running /opt/<SIU>/MYDIR/bin/saveconfig should give the same results as "normal" saveconfig.

Funniest of all, this functionality should be also supported on Windows, including the symlinks creation functionality!

If you are still reading here, I suppose you are a maniac. Then, I trust, you would not mind to test one more thing: specifying something like:

saveconfig cli ../../bin

...to try and create a command in /bin should not work!

Thanks a lot for your coÃ¶peration!

ID: QXCR1001534010

State: Completed

Visibility: Lab, Support & Customer

Engineer: Chernyavsky,Ivan [chernyavsky@hpe.com]

Content Reviewed?: Y

Symptoms:

On Unix, eIUM's main startup script (/etc/init.d/SIU) should allow plugging in additional services, such as CIS or the License Server. As an additional requirement, the main script and individual services should support a "restart" command, in addition to "start" and "stop".

Resolution:

The main eIUM service script (/etc/init.d/SIU) has been enhanced to allow option bundles (formerly "product extensions"), such as the License Server, to plug in their own services. It is now possible to start/stop/restart all installed and enabled services by running /etc/init.d/SIU {start|stop|restart}. It is also possible to start/stop/restart individual services by running commands like /etc/init.d/SIU license_start. When called without parameters, /etc/init.d/SIU will provide some information on available options and enabled services.

Submitter Text Notes:

On Unix, IUM's main startup script (/etc/init.d/SIU) should allow to plug-in additional services such as VNFM or License Server.

As an additional requirement, main script and individual services should support "restart" command in addition to "start" and "stop".

Test Info Notes:

Please ensure that when VNFM and/or LS are installed, corresponding "subservices" ("vnfm", "license") are shown in the output of /etc/init.d/SIU script.

When called without parameters, /etc/init.d/SIU should show a decent description of possible options.

It should be possible to start/stop all of them by /etc/init.d/SIU {start|stop}.

It should be also possible to start/stop individual subservices by e.g. /etc/init.d/SIU vnfm_start.

It should be also possible to restart all (/etc/init.d/SIU restart) or individual subservice (/etc/init.d/SIU vnfm_restart).

Verifier: 

eIUM90 RC5a
RHEL 7x64
Java 8u112
=====================

It was verified that new Unix startup scripts work as expected.
